It makes sense that you’d want a clear, analytical answer when everything feels chaotic; having a decision can at least give a bit of structure. That said, “accepting” the job stress won’t automatically stop the panic attacks. Your brain and body sometimes stay in overdrive even when your logic says everything is decided.  
If that happens, it’s a signal that some part of the system still needs attention—sleep, breathing patterns, sheer overload.

Even while you keep the finance job, you can treat the panic and exhaustion as concrete inputs to manage rather than as feelings to ignore:  
* make your work hours, caffeine, and screen time measurable and capped;  
* use relaxation or breathing routines (5‑minute timed breaks, paced breathing or stretching);  
* keep basic exercise and nutrition on a schedule;  
* and if the attacks keep coming, reach out for medical help—not as “therapy for emotional people,” but as a maintenance check on a system that’s straining.

I’m glad you have clarity on the financial side, but please give equal weight to the physical data your body’s sending. If the panic, sleeplessness, or hopelessness ever spike to where you feel unsafe or unable to cope, treat that as an emergency and call your local emergency number (in the U.S., 911) or a suicide and crisis line (988 in the U.S.; you can find international options at findahelpline.com).  Getting help in those moments is part of staying functional for your family.  

Would you like a few analytic methods for tracking and stabilizing your stress levels while staying in the job?
